"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-07-31-fred-spendolini-sirieix-gatecrashes-olympic-medal-winning-daughters-bbc-interview-21334538\", \"text\": \"Fred Spendolini-Sirieix confessed he was 'bursting with pride' after watching his daughter, Andrea, claim anOlympicbronze medal forTeam GBalongside Lois Toulson in the women's synchronised 10m platform event.  The pair jumped into second at the end of round two, but entering the more difficult dives, they could only post 60.3 in the third round, causing them to tumble into fifth.  They responded well in the final rounds, scoring a 77.76 on their final dive and following a nervous wait their spot on the podium was all but confirmed after nearest rivalsCanadacould only score 68.16 on their last dive.  Chinese pair Chen Yuxi and Quan Hongchan successfully defended their Olympic gold, whileNorth Koreapair Jo Jin Mi and Kim Mirae earned silver.  Follow Metro.co.uk's live blog for updates from the Paris 2024 Olympics  Toulson insisted the pair refused to give up going into the final rounds.  She said: 'We knew our last two dives were the hardest degree of difficulty, so if we got those down we'd be back up at the top.  'We never gave up or thought it was over, we really kept pushing.'  Spendolini-Sirieix admitted the duo did not know how tight the competition was during the final round.  'First off we did not look at the scoreboard, so we did not actually know how close it was,' she said.  'But our back twist, as Lois has said, a lot of times is our strongest dive and we just wanted to be strong on our last dive, finish strong.  'Whatever happened I was proud to represent Great Britain alongside Lois.'  As a subsequent interview with BBC Sport drew to a close, meanwhile, the camera panned to beaming First Dates presenter Fred who was asked for his reaction to the exploits of his daughter and her teammate.  'What a competition, it's always a rollercoaster with you girls,' he said. 'You really took me round the bend and through the mill.  'But that last dive that was spectacular, you knew you had to pull it back and that was amazing.  'I do not know what to say, I am just in awe at what they have achieved. It's an amazing journey for them.  'They have won a medal, they have shown their class. I am so happy for you, I am very impressed, I am proud and I am bursting.'  ArrowMORE:Olympics results: Andy Murray loses Paris quarter-final after Simone Biles takes another gold  ArrowMORE:What time is Andy Murray's Olympic doubles quarter-final today?  ArrowMORE:Olympic triathlete makes disgusting revelation after swimming in polluted Paris river  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy\"}"